{"source_key":"sha256-c39b43a4abcd57aa78dc3aa06966371a","record_index":58,"record_hash":"sha256:77fbdc82eb9cc591f86eff8433624c498191987d8281be12791eaecb3028df57","timestamp":"2026-05-20T05:04:17.254Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: d8c10e\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1494\nOutput:\nthey can be stored as optional record-level grouping metadata, preferably as a\nsafe provider turn key rather than a raw provider id.\n\nMinimum useful fields:\n\n- capture turn id\n- session key\n- source key\n- capture kind\n- capture timestamp\n- transcript record membership, probably by record hash and/or source record\n  index\n- optional provider turn key on transcript records, for grouping/display only\n- previous turn reference, when there is a previous capture turn in the same\n  session\n- environment snapshot\n\nThe record membership matters because `but-agentlog` already deduplicates\nrecords. Without turn membership, repeated hook capture preserves the transcript\nbut erases the boundaries between capture invocations.\n\n`TurnDetail.records` must be an ordered array. That order is authoritative for\nrendering records within a capture turn; hashes and source indexes identify the\nrecords, but they are not a replacement for sequence.\n\nThe model should distinguish:\n\n- **capture turn:** a stop-hook capture observation with new transcript records\n  and a repository environment snapshot\n- **provider turn:** a provider-native conversation grouping, such as a user\n  prompt and the resulting assistant/tool activity\n\nCapture turns are the durable agentlog concept. Provider turns are useful for UI\ngrouping when available, but they are not portable enough to define the storage\nmodel across agents.\n\nStore `previous_turn_key` as a session-wide previous capture turn pointer when\nit is available. It is not part of capture turn identity. It exists to make\ninterval evidence cheap to evaluate, for example \"worktree files seen in the\nprevious turn later appeared in commits visible in this turn.\" The first capture\nturn omits the field.\n\nImplementation should write transcript records, record hashes, the capture turn\nobject, the turn summary list entry, and derived index entries as one logical\nGitMeta update.\nIf transcript record write\n[TRUNCATED]\nple a pull request\n- commits in each branch\n- optional change id for each commit\n- files changed by each commit\n\nAlso store a compact `observed_targets` summary on the turn detail. It should\ncontain the canonical branch, review, and change keys that were indexed for this\nturn. This keeps candidate verification and future index rebuilds cheap without\nduplicating the whole environment snapshot in every reader.\n`observed_targets` is a deterministic projection of `environment`, not a second\nsource of truth. Writers derive it from the same snapshot in the same atomic\nwrite. Readers may verify index hits against it before reading the heavier\nenvironment detail.\n\nPlain Git mode should use the same snapshot path as GitButler mode. The\nexpectation is that the GitButler workspace/head-info APIs expose a compatible\nstack/branch shape for plain Git repositories, so `but-agentlog` should not grow\na separate plain-Git fallback model unless the shared API proves insufficient.\n\nGitButler mode is more nuanced:\n\n- there may be multiple applied branches/stacks at the same time\n- there may be zero applied branches\n- stacked branches may mean both `bottom-refactor` and `top-feature` are\n  present, while the agent session is only relevant to `top-feature`\n- two applied branches such as `my-feature` and `other-stuff` may coexist even\n  when only one is relevant to the session\n\nDo not store a separate `checked_out_refs` field. It duplicates the stack/branch\nsnapshot and creates reader precedence questions. Also do not store graph\nprojection internals such as `is_entrypoint`; that is a traversal detail, not\ndurable product evidence for association.\n\nBranch names, relative file paths, review identifiers, change ids, commit ids,\nand commit file lists are acceptable for repo-scoped `gitbutler:*` metadata\nbecause they travel within the same repository metadata access boundary as the\ncode. Do not store absolute paths. Re-check this assumption before exposing the\nsame metadata in product surfaces with a narrower audience than repository\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T05:04:17.254Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}